Flight from Moscow
The collapse of communism gave the nations of the former Soviet bloc the chance to turn towards democracy, market economy, and the rule of law.
Some of these countries broke decisively with their communist past; others were less successful, and a few catastrophically failed.
Moldova and Georgia belonged until recently to the latter category.
Their economic and political failure was largely based on – actively supported by Russia – secessionist movements that tried to keep both countries within the "sphere of influence" of the Kremlin.
As bloody conflicts broke out in Transnistria, Abkhazia and South Ossetia, Russia transformed its military presence in the region into "peacekeeping troops" to maintain control.
For a long time, one feared that these so-called "frozen conflicts" could suddenly turn into hot ones.
Not only has this not happened, but we can now speak of solutions – because both Georgia and Moldova have begun to achieve a breakthrough towards market economy and democracy.
This has also been contributed to by the European Union's "neighborhood policy".
The starting point of these developments was the "Rose Revolution" in Georgia three years ago.
Close to collapse, Georgia has meanwhile turned to the West.
The success of the various "color revolutions" in former Soviet bloc countries has also triggered change in Moldova. Here, President Vladimir Voronin launched reforms whose goal is to draw closer to the EU.
These changes have triggered new initiatives in Georgia and Moldova to restore the territorial integrity of these countries through peaceful means.
The experience of Estonia suggests how Georgia and Moldova should shape their policy towards Russia.
When Estonia gained independence in 1991, Moscow sought to portray Estonia as an economically troubled country, unsuitable for investment.
Estland was indeed poor, and its main export products were scrap metal and wood, yet its economy was growing.
In northeast Estonia with a predominantly Russian-speaking population that had settled there during the Soviet era, Russia supported a so-called "autonomy movement".
As Estonia resisted, Russia imposed sanctions and cut off the gas supplies.
Taxes were levied on the few Estonian products that were allowed to be imported into Russia, and Russia even threatened with a military intervention.
But Estonia kept its nerves.
The Russian sanctions even helped the country to reorient its economy in the direction of the West.
Conversely, Western Europe did what it could to integrate the Baltic states – Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia – and at the same time sought to avoid a conflict with Russia.
In 1994, a free trade agreement with the EU enabled Estonian products to find new markets, and so Estonia ultimately became one of the most successful post-communist transition countries and joined the EU and NATO in 2004.
However, when Georgia became independent in 1991, it did not receive the same support from Western Europe.
Of course, Georgia appeared to be a less attractive partner than the Baltic states; the 1990s were marked by coups, countercoups and civil wars, with two regions – Abkhazia and South Ossetia – virtually seceding with the support of Russia.
The country has done its best to forget its dismal past.
Since the Rose Revolution, the economy has been reformed, the army strengthened, and the country's leadership is young, dynamic, and enthusiastically devoted to moving the country forward.
Thanks to Georgia's flat-rate income tax of 12% – probably the lowest in the world – the national budget has increased.
The government has raised pensions and increased social benefits.
Corruption is decreasing, and a judicial reform has been initiated.
The economy grew by 8% in 2005 and over 10% in 2006.
Georgia has been making an effort to ease the tensions around Abkhazia and South Ossetia; but Russia accuses the country of aggression and ethnic cleansing.
Its main goal is to prevent the West from supporting Georgia and to prevent a reconciliation with the secessionist regions.
The powers that matter in Georgia are Russia and to a certain extent the United States.
Europe must show that it is also of importance.
Estland hat – bei seiner Unabhängigkeit und erneut während der jüngsten Krise über die Verlagerung eines Denkmals aus der Sowjetzeit – gezeigt, dass man sich mit Entschlossenheit und starker Unterstützung dem russischen Druck widersetzen kann.
Europe must understand that Georgia needs trade, not humanitarian aid.
Just as the free trade agreement with Europe enabled Estonia to find new markets, this can be the means by which the Georgians can help themselves.
Georgia has justifiable reason to hope that it will achieve a true independence. But what about Moldova, the poorest country in Europe, which is threatened more by Russia than the Estonians or even the Georgians ever were?
The missing reform successes are partly the result of the secessionist movements supported by Russia.
Dass sich die industrialisierte Region Transnistrien – deren russisch und ukrainisch sprechende Bevölkerung fürchtete, die Mehrheit der Moldauer, die rumänischer Abstammung ist, plane engere Verbindungen zu Rumänien – von Moldau lossagte, hat der Unabhängigkeit des Landes gleich zu Beginn einen schweren Schlag versetzt.
Es folgte ein Bürgerkrieg, and in the year 1992 Russian troops marched into Transnistria, where they are still today.
The independence of Transnistria was never recognized – neither by Moldova nor internationally.
It is said that there reigns lawlessness and corruption there.
Moldova is heavily indebted, unemployment is high, and its once-renowned wine industry is in decline.
Russia occasionally cuts off the gas supplies, and many of the four million citizens have left the country.
Only Russia can solve the problem.
Government representatives of Moldova have made four fruitless visits to Moscow to persuade President Vladimir Putin to take action and withdraw the Russian troops.
A desperate Voronin has asked for help from the EU observer mission Eubam, but an EU initiative would require Russian cooperation.
Unfortunately, it seems that the West lacks up-to-date knowledge about the situation in Moldova.
In April, for example, the EU and the US learned about a proposed peace agreement through a leaked report from Germany.
This, as it seems, would favor Russia, as Moldova would have to recognize Transnistria as a legitimate unit within it.
If Russia has outmaneuvered the West in this way, this would be a malignant precedent for Georgia and other weak post-communist states.
